[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You know, recently we\'ve been hit with kind of an embarrassment of riches in AI video editing. Not like timeline traditional editing, of course, but rather the nano banana-ing of video, which is more akin to VFX or post-work. But, with the added benefit of it being'

[00:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generative, so it\'s stupid fast and smart. The three biggest releases thus far have been Google\'s Omni model, Runway\'s Aleph 2, and well, some don\'t realize this, but SeaDance 2.0. Plus,'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'re going to take a bit of a preview look at what I think is going to be a major shake-up in AI video workflows. And no, it\'s not nodes. Don\'t worry, node haters. But, it will be popping up a lot more in the upcoming days. So, you'

[00:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'know, consider this a look to get a jump on it. All right, let\'s hop in. Kicking off, you know, if there\'s one thing that kind of bugs me about the vocabulary around AI image and video, and I will fully admit this is old man yells at cloud, but it\'s the term'

[00:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'editing. At least in the traditional sense, editing is, well, using a razor or at least the icon of a razor to, well, I mean, cut and splice two clips together. Now, in the Gen AI world, editing can encompass anything from,'

[01:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'well, VFX work to roto-ing to ADR-ing. And look, I\'m not going to get too lost in the woods here on like the lexicon, but recently we have seen a new class of tools that go beyond all of this and well, into the world of generative'

[01:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 're-shooting. Google\'s Omni, which is kind of the surprise left turn that was not VEO-4, did end up making a big splash with its ability to, well, nano banana of videos. So, essentially, you could do almost anything you want. On the heels of that release, Runway'

[01:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dropped version two of its Aleph feature, which, you know, on the surface, does look very similar, but as we\'ll see today, actually is different. And surprisingly, I mean, I guess maybe people did not know this, but reigning king of AI video, SeaDance 2.0, is also'

[01:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'capable of doing very Omni-like things. But, also, all three of them are different models that all have their own unique strengths and flaws. Um so I figured today we could run through some'

[02:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tests to see where each one is. Kicking off with a fairly simple test for these types of models, a simple restyle. We\'re going to be utilizing this piece of stock footage. And actually we\'re going to begin on Runway because I think it\'s kind of important to see how Aleph'

[02:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'works. So with Aleph or Aleph, I I\'m going to be going back and forth on that all video long. I just want you to know that in advance. Somebody in the comments let me know how you correctly pronounce that. Um so what we what the way this works is that essentially you'

[02:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pick a frame from your input video and then you can make changes to it. And those changes will apply either via Nano Banana Pro, Image 2, or Gen 4. So essentially it creates a still image and then from there when you run the model,'

[02:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you know, essentially those changes will be applied to the output video. So in this case, I just gave it the prompt to give it a dark animated look with like an apocalypse city in the background.'

[02:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is actually generated up in Nano Banana Pro. Um so firing this off, I\'d say Runway delivers. It gives us what we asked for. Um all the motion is present. Camera move is present. Little bit of'

[03:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'smudging in the face and some of the details, but you know, overall I think it looks pretty solid. The same driving video and reference image now in Google\'s Omni, which I think does a pretty good job. It definitely improves'

[03:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on the image like fidelity and quality. Um lot more details in our character\'s face there. Does catch the shadow in the background, which is pretty impressive. I do think it the movement does look a'

[03:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'little bit more on the stiff side to me. Um but you know, overall I think a pretty solid job. Also like the camera does like kind of a weird movement thing. Like it doesn\'t quite catch the tracking of the camera in the original'

[03:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video. And finally over on SeaDance, which I mean to be honest is probably the best of the three. Um it does definitely retain most of the movement of our original driving video and the camera movement as well while managing'

[03:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to re-stylize everything. Uh, I mean, really truly the only criticism that I have on this is uh, that the smoke remains, you know, kind of photo-realistic smoke and doesn\'t actually change out to the animated look. But look, I\'m not going to dock it'

[04:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'points on that one. Our next test is in essentially basic cleanup. Um, this is a weird issue that I was running into the other day with C Dance where I kept getting like these odd like scan lines across the output. Let\'s take a quick'

[04:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'look at the original video. &gt;&gt; Possible contact bearing 185. &gt;&gt; So, kicking that edit off with C Dance kind of make C Dance fix yourself, C Dance. Um, we end up with this.'

[04:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Possible contact bearing 185. &gt;&gt; Which did solve the problem that I asked it to. Uh, like we did remove those like interpolation scan lines, but it also'

[04:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'did get a little heavy-handed and removed essentially all of the data on the screen. Google\'s Omni, which I did utilize over on Flow, actually did work. Uh, take a look at that real quick. &gt;&gt; Possible contact bearing 185.'

[05:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
